          "body": "The *ish beliyyaal* (worthless man, v. 12) is described from the outside in: mouth (perverse speech), eyes (winking), feet (signaling), fingers (pointing), heart (devising evil), mouth again (spreading strife). The body-inventory is deliberate — every member is an instrument of deception. The father then elevates the argument to the divine perspective with the numerical saying (vv. 16-19), a Hebrew device where 'n + 1' signals the final item as the climax. The list maps across the same body parts: eyes (pride), tongue (lying), hands (violent), heart (scheming), feet (rushing), mouth (false witness), and then the capstone — the sower of strife among brothers. The move from human portrait to divine hatred is not decorative theology; it grounds the social consequences of vv. 12-15 in something more permanent than social shame. God's aversion to these behaviors is principled and settled (*sane*), and the abomination (*toevah*) language connects social deceit to the same category as idolatry in Deuteronomy. The theological weight is substantial: the community-destroying manipulator is not merely a social problem but a theological offense."
