        "title": "Deliver yourself urgently — the snare of the pledged word",
        "range": "6:1-5",
        "excerpt": "Deliver yourself like a gazelle from the hunter's hand and like a bird from the hand of the fowler.",
        "body": "The opening unit assumes a fait accompli. The son has already become surety — *arav* (struck hands, entered into pledge) — for a neighbor's debt, possibly to a stranger (*zur*, an outsider to the covenant community). The verb *taqa* (to drive, thrust, strike) was the technical term for the handshake-pledge that formalized a surety agreement in ancient Israelite commerce. He did not sin in making the pledge, but he has created a legal vulnerability that could ruin him if the neighbor defaults.\n\nThe father's response is not consolation; it is a tactical brief. Three imperatives in verse 3 — go, humble yourself (*raphas*: literally to stomp, to trample, to submit with urgency), importune (*rahav*: to press boldly, importune with persistence). Then two more: give no sleep to your eyes, no slumber to your eyelids (v. 4). The combination of urgency and humility is striking. Pride is the natural reflex — the son may want to wait and see, or to avoid the awkwardness of admitting a mistake to the neighbor. The father forecloses that option entirely: embarrassment is the cheapest price you will pay in this situation.\n\nThe gazelle and the bird (v. 5) are not decorative similes. Both animals were hunted in ancient Israel — the gazelle (*tsevi*) was prized game, the birds of the fowler's net (*yaqush*) were small birds caught in spring traps. Both images share the element of a snare already sprung: the gazelle has caught the hunter's eye, the bird has touched the net. At that point, only one thing matters — speed and full expenditure of energy to escape. Dignity, rest, and social comfort are not available options.\n\nThe canonical resonance points backward to Proverbs 11:15 ('he who is guarantor for a stranger will surely suffer for it') and forward to 22:26-27 ('do not be among those who give pledges, among those who become guarantors for debts; if you have nothing with which to pay, why should he take your bed from under you?'). This is not an isolated warning but a repeating Proverbial axiom. The wisdom tradition is unanimous: surety agreements entered carelessly are financial traps, and the exit requires the kind of humility and urgency the self-preserving heart resists.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Arav* (to put up surety, 6:1) — the root carries a sense of mingling or intermixing; the guarantor has entangled his own financial fate with the debtor's. *Raphas* (humble yourself, 6:3) is a vivid verb: to trample, to stamp, to lower oneself with force — not mild meekness but urgent self-abasement. *Natsal* (deliver yourself, 6:5) appears twice in the unit (vv. 3 and 5), a rescue term used elsewhere for divine deliverance — the intensity of the military rescue idiom is applied to a commercial situation."
