        "title": "The worthless man and seven abominations — deceit as divine offense",
        "range": "6:12-19",
        "excerpt": "There are six things which the LORD hates, yes, seven which are an abomination to Him.",
        "body": "The portrait of the *ish beliyyaal* (man of worthlessness, v. 12) is constructed by tracking his body parts. His mouth is perverse (*iqqshut*, crooked, twisted — 6:12). His eyes wink signals, his feet communicate by motion, his fingers point covert messages (6:13). This is a man whose entire body has become an instrument of deceptive communication — what he says openly and what he signals covertly are different. The heart that drives all of this (v. 14) is characterized by *tahpukhah* — perversity, deliberate inversion of the right order — and he is *continually* (*tamid*) devising evil. This is not occasional sin but settled orientation. The result is that he spreads *medan* (strife, discord) — community fracture is the final product of a deceiving body and a corrupt heart.\n\nThe consequence (v. 15) arrives suddenly and totally. *Pitom* (suddenly) and *peta* (in an instant) are stacked — the sage underscores the discontinuous nature of the ruin. And there is no *marpe* — no healing, no remedy, no restoration. The same word appears in 2 Chronicles 21:18, Jeremiah 14:19, and notably in Proverbs 29:1 ('a man who hardens his neck after much reproof will suddenly be broken beyond remedy'). The irremediability is not incidental; it is the text's theological assertion that some patterns of life exhaust the possibility of recovery.\n\nThe seven-abomination list (vv. 16-19) elevates the argument from social consequence to divine character. The LORD *hates* (*sane*) — a verb of principled aversion, not emotional volatility. The seven items are presented as an anatomical map: haughty eyes (pride of vision), lying tongue, hands that shed innocent blood, a heart devising wicked plans, feet that run to evil, a false witness who breathes out lies, and — as the climactic seventh — the one who sows strife among brothers. The '6 + 7' numerical device is a Semitic climactic form (cf. Amos 1-2; Job 5:19) where the final item is the capstone, the one that exceeds the rest.\n\nThe word *toevah* (abomination, v. 16) is the Hebrew vocabulary's strongest term for divine moral revulsion. In Deuteronomy it is consistently applied to idolatry (7:25-26; 12:31; 17:1). To apply it here to the sower of strife is a canonical claim: community fracture is as offensive to God as idol worship. The relational sin is not a lesser category than the cultic one. This is one of the most important moves in the chapter's theology — it prevents the reader from ranking sins hierarchically in ways God does not.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Beliyyaal* (worthless, 6:12) — the term entered later Jewish literature as a proper noun for the embodiment of evil (Belial), attested in the Dead Sea Scrolls. *Toevah* (abomination, 6:16) — 117 occurrences in the OT, 43 in Deuteronomy alone, typically for idolatry; the application to the strife-sower makes the social sin categorically equivalent to cultic violation. *Medan* (strife/discord, 6:14, 19) — appears exclusively in Proverbs, always in the context of deliberately sown conflict."
