        "number": 4,
        "title": "The commandment as lamp — wisdom's protective function",
        "range": "6:20-23",
        "excerpt": "For the commandment is a lamp and the teaching is light; and reproofs for discipline are the way of life.",
        "body": "The transition from the abomination list to the adulteress warning is bridged by the father's most sustained positive statement in the chapter. After six verses of divine hate (vv. 16-19), he rebuilds the constructive architecture: keep the commandment of your father (*mitsvah*), do not forsake the teaching of your mother (*torah*). The pairing of *mitsvah* and *torah* here is not the Mosaic Law; it is the parental instruction being transmitted in the Proverbs discourse itself. But the terms deliberately echo Deuteronomy's language for Torah (cf. Deuteronomy 6:1-9), elevating parental wisdom to a quasi-revelatory status within the family covenant.\n\nThe embodiment language of verse 21 is striking: bind them continually (*tamid*) on your heart, tie them around your neck. This recalls Deuteronomy 6:8 (bind them as a sign on your hand, let them be frontlets between your eyes) and anticipates Proverbs 7:3 (bind them on your fingers, write them on the tablet of your heart). The father wants wisdom internalized — not memorized as external data but woven into the body's daily rhythms. A wisdom tied around the neck accompanies every conversation; a wisdom bound on the heart governs every decision before the decision is consciously made.\n\nVerse 22 tracks the full cycle of daily life: walking (active, mobile life), sleeping (vulnerable, unconscious life), awaking (transition, the moment of new choices). At every stage the internalized commandment is present — guiding, watching, speaking. The three verbs (*nachah*: guide like a shepherd; *shamar*: guard, watch over; *siach*: meditate, speak to you) frame wisdom as a personal companion and counselor rather than a rule-book consulted occasionally.\n\nThe lamp-and-light metaphor of verse 23 is the chapter's hermeneutical key. Lamp (*ner*) provides localized, immediate guidance — what is directly in front of you. Light (*or*) is broader illumination — general orientation. Together they suggest that the commandment provides both tactical guidance (which step to take next) and strategic orientation (which direction life is going). The 'reproofs for discipline as the way of life' is an inversion of expectation: correction feels like an obstacle but functions as the road. Spurgeon's observation is apt here — the men who felt most corrected by Scripture proved most protected by it.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Mitsvah* (commandment) and *torah* (teaching/law) — the father uses the language of divine revelation for parental instruction, a deliberate and important move. *Tamid* (continually, 6:21) — the same word used for the perpetual burnt offering in the tabernacle (Exodus 29:42); the teaching is to be as constant as temple worship. *Ner* (lamp) and *or* (light) appear together in Psalm 119:105 ('Your word is a lamp to my feet and a light to my path') — the verbal parallel is exact."
