        "number": 5,
        "title": "The adulteress and the fire — consequences that cannot be purchased away",
        "range": "6:24-35",
        "excerpt": "Can a man take fire in his bosom and his clothes not be burned?",
        "body": "The adulteress warning of Proverbs 6 is the second of three extended treatments in chapters 5-7, and it is the most legally and consequentially specific. Chapter 5 warned by appeal to regret and marital covenant; chapter 7 will warn by narrative seduction — the foolish young man who follows her to his death. Chapter 6 warns by appeal to irreversibility: the consequences of adultery, unlike those of theft, cannot be settled. This is a unique rhetorical register.\n\nThe section begins in the interior — 'do not desire her beauty in your heart' (v. 25). The point of entry for the sin is desire (*chamad*, the same verb as the tenth commandment, 'you shall not covet'). The father identifies the heart's appetite as the battlefield, not the street corner where the adulteress operates. Then the eyelids capture (v. 25b) — the gaze follows the desire, and once the gaze is captured, the body follows. This is the sequence James will later name with precision: desire → conception → birth → death (James 1:14-15). Proverbs anticipates the anthropology.\n\nThe two descents of verse 26 are staggered by severity: the harlot (*zanah*) reduces a man to a loaf of bread — financial ruin; the adulteress (*ishshah*) hunts for the precious life (*nephesh*) — existential destruction. The escalation signals that the danger is not primarily economic but ontological: she is not taking your money; she is taking *you*.\n\nThe fire-and-coals argument of verses 27-29 is the chapter's most compressed logic: two physical impossibilities (you cannot carry fire without your clothes burning; you cannot walk on coals without your feet scorching) and one social conclusion (so is the one who goes in to his neighbor's wife). The arguments are not theological; they are causal. The sage is pressing the son toward inevitability: this is how reality works. Some things that feel manageable are not. Fire is fire.\n\nThe thief comparison (vv. 30-35) is the chapter's most sophisticated rhetorical move. The sage does not say theft is acceptable — the thief is still punished (v. 31: sevenfold repayment, all the substance of his house). But his crime has a comprehensible motive (hunger) and a resolvable penalty (property). The adulterer's crime has no comprehensible wisdom-motive (v. 32: he 'lacks sense') and no resolvable penalty (v. 35: no ransom, no gift, no satisfaction). The offended husband's *qinah* (jealousy/zeal — the same word used of God's zeal for His covenant, Exodus 20:5) fuels a *chemah* (burning anger, v. 34) that will not accept monetary settlement. Property crimes are repairable. Honor crimes are not. The chapter ends not with forgiveness but with permanent disgrace (v. 33: 'his reproach will not be blotted out') — the *machah* (to wipe away) negated. This is Proverbs functioning as wisdom law, not gospel: it shows the consequences of the path before the foot falls, without promising a remedy once it does.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Chamad* (desire/lust, 6:25) — the Decalogue's verb for covetousness (Exodus 20:17; Deuteronomy 5:21); the adulteress section is deliberately placed in the lexical field of commandment-violation. *Nephesh* (life/soul, 6:26, 32) — the whole self, not merely physical life; the adulteress takes a man's entire person. *Qinah* (jealousy, 6:34) — the covenant-jealousy term applied to God in the Decalogue; the cuckolded husband embodies a human analogue of divine zeal for covenant fidelity. *Machah* (blotted out, 6:33) — negated: the reproach cannot be erased, not even by future righteousness."
